{
  "doc_id": "33214",
  "text": "In an attempt to prevent illicit use, companies are working to develop abuse deterrent formulas. Acura Pharmaceuticals is one of the leading companies in this and has patented what they call \"Aversion Technology\". This technology aims to make it more difficult and uncomfortable to extract the active ingredient from opioid pills and use them intravenously or through the nasal passage [CITATION_1] . For example, when mixed with a solvent the pill will turn into a gel and when ingested through the nasal passage it will cause increased burning and irritation [CITATION_2] . This proposed preventative measure might be more designed for manufacturers to maintain sales than to confront the opioid crisis. Research from the University of Toronto suggests that tamper-resistant formulas may only be effective in deterring individuals who intend to manipulate a medication [CITATION_3] . Apart from that, they have not been effective in preventing addiction or death [CITATION_4] . Overall, this strategy fails to recognize that many illicit users begin as prescribed users and ultimately, it enables the continuation of opioid access and distribution.",
